compose_pack: structured authoring so agents never carry the grammar in context

The founder's concern: working through MCP, an agent should NOT need the whole
DSL grammar in context to describe an entity. Solution: a structured authoring
tool. The agent passes JSON intent (entities with typed fields, workflows,
roles, permission rules); the node RENDERS the DSL server-side and validates it.
The grammar lives on the node; the agent's "grammar knowledge" is just the
tool's JSON schema, delivered by MCP tools/list — not prose in context.

- internal/dsl/compose.go: PackSpec -> DSL renderer (same text a human writes,
  then compiled normally — one source of truth)
- MCP tools: compose_pack (JSON spec -> rendered+validated DSL), field_types
- the DSL stays the human/diff artifact; agents author via structure
- tested: a JSON ticket pack renders to DSL that compiles
